onal name based on <i>dál</i> (modern <i>dáil</i>) ‘meeting, assembly’.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Dally   2."]},{"name":"Alyea","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>D'Ailly</b> or   Dailly  . Compare   Allee   2 and   Elyea  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with several variants, including <i>Allée</i>, and the original form <i>d'Ailly</i>). The Huguenot ancestor was Nicolas d'Ailly, who came from France to NY <i>c.</i> 1682 via the Netherlands and England and died in NJ <i>c.</i> 1700."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":0,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":10,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert d'Oilly the Y